<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-282-112  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 282 112.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 11 1989 n1163 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Holding the mainframe fortress. (computer security againstviruses)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jones, Keith.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Although mainframe computers are much less vulnerable to virusattacks than microcomputers, the effects of such attacks could befar worse.andP;  The most damaging attack would be one that affects themainframe operating system itself.andP;  Most modern commercialmainframe operating systems are secure if all security featuresare used, but often this is not the case.andP;  Programs are writtenthat bypass security features, and trapdoors are left in thesystem.andP;  For example, a virus could damage the IBM MVS operatingsystem's Authorized Program Facility simply by waiting to beexecuted by a user with update access privileges.andP;  Anotherdisruptive mechanism is the Trojan Horse, or any method thattricks someone with authority into performing or allowing afunction that aids an outsider.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   MVS (Operating system) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Computer VirusesMainframe ComputersSecurityTrapdoorsComputer CrimesAccess MethodsSabotageVandalism.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Andy Holt. (portrait)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>